==English==
===Etymology===
From {{suffix|absolute|ness}}.

===Pronunciation===
*{{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈabsəluːtnəs/|/absəˈluːtnəs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|es}}

# {{obsolete}} The fact of being [[finished]] or [[perfected]]; [[completeness]]. {{defdate|16th-17th c.}}
# Absolute [[authority]], unlimited power; [[despotism]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#*'''1603''', {{w|John Florio}}, translating Michel de Montaigne, ''Essays'', II.8:
#*:I know no man that could produce more parts, both naturall and artificiall, fit to preserve his masterie, and to maintaine his '''absolutenesse''', than he doth; yet is hee cleane falne from them like a childe.
# The fact of being without qualifications or conditions; [[certainty]], unconditionality. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
# Independent [[autonomy]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}

